[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] The **`EventSource`** interface is web content's interface to server-sent events.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] An `EventSource` instance opens a persistent connection to an HTTP server, which sends events in `text/event-stream` format.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] The connection remains open until closed by calling `EventSource.close()`.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Once the connection is opened, incoming messages from the server are delivered to your code in the form of events.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] If there is an event field in the incoming message, the triggered event is the same as the event field value.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] If no event field is present, then a generic `message` event is fired.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Unlike WebSockets, server-sent events are unidirectional; that is, data messages are delivered in one direction, from the server to the client (such as a user's web browser).
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] That makes them an excellent choice when there's no need to send data from the client to the server in message form.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] For example, `EventSource` is a useful approach for handling things like social media status updates, news feeds, or delivering data into a client-side storage mechanism like IndexedDB or web storage.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Creates a new `EventSource` to handle receiving server-sent events from a specified URL, optionally in credentials mode.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] A number representing the state of the connection.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] A string representing the URL of the source.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] A boolean value indicating whether the `EventSource` object was instantiated with cross-origin (CORS) credentials set (`true`), or not (`false`, the default).
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Closes the connection, if any, and sets the `readyState` attribute to `CLOSED`.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] If the connection is already closed, the method does nothing.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Fired when a connection to an event source failed to open.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Fired when data is received from an event source.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Fired when a connection to an event source has opened.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Additionally, the event source itself may send messages with an event field, which will create ad hoc events keyed to that value.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] In this basic example, an `EventSource` is created to receive unnamed events from the server; a page with the name `sse.php` is responsible for generating the events.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] Each received event causes our `EventSource` object's `onmessage` event handler to be run.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] It, in turn, creates a new `<li>` element and writes the message's data into it, then appends the new element to the list element already in the document.
[src:websockets-browser/api-eventsource] To listen to named events, you'll require a listener for each type of event sent.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] The `WebSocket` object provides the API for creating and managing a WebSocket connection to a server, as well as for sending and receiving data on the connection.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] To construct a `WebSocket`, use the `WebSocket()` constructor.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Returns a newly created `WebSocket` object.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] The binary data type used by the connection.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] The sub-protocol selected by the server.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Fired when a connection with a `WebSocket` is closed.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Fired when a connection with a `WebSocket` has been closed because of an error, such as when some data couldn't be sent.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Also available via the `onerror` property.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Fired when data is received through a `WebSocket`.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Also available via the `onmessage` property.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Fired when a connection with a `WebSocket` is opened.
[src:websockets-browser/api-websocket] Also available via the `onopen` property.
[src:websockets-browser/server-sent-events] All modern browsers support server-sent events: Firefox 6+, Google Chrome 6+, Opera 11.5+, Safari 5+, Microsoft Edge 79+, Brave.
[src:websockets-browser/server-sent-events] Since SSE does not use either persistent connections nor chunked transfer encoding, HTTP/1.1 is not a technical requirement.
[src:websockets-browser/server-sent-events] The SSE mechanism was first specified by Ian Hickson as part of the "WHATWG Web Applications 1.0" proposal starting in 2004.
[src:websockets-browser/server-sent-events] In September 2006, the Opera web browser implemented the experimental technology in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:websockets-browser/server-sent-events] The W3C published Server-Sent Events as a Recommendation on February 3, 2015, after years of development through Working Drafts and Candidate Recommendations.
[src:websockets-browser/server-sent-events] When sending high-frequency data , the server must manage backpressure to prevent saturating clients.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:websockets-browser/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] The **WebSocket API** makes it possible to open a two-way interactive communication session between the user's browser and a server.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] With this API, you can send messages to a server and receive responses without having to poll the server for a reply.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] The WebSocket API provides two alternative mechanisms for creating and using web socket connections: the `WebSocket` interface and the `WebSocketStream` interface.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] Additionally, the WebTransport API is expected to replace the WebSocket API for many applications.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] WebTransport is a versatile, low-level API that provides backpressure and many other features not supported by either `WebSocket` or `WebSocketStream`, such as unidirectional streams, out-of-order delivery, and unreliable data transmission via datagrams.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] WebTransport is more complex to use than WebSockets and its cross-browser support is not as wide, but it enables the implementation of sophisticated solutions.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] If standard WebSocket connections are a good fit for your use case and you need wide browser compatibility, you should employ the WebSockets API to get up and running quickly.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] However, if your application requires a non-standard custom solution, then you should use the WebTransport API.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] The primary interface for connecting to a WebSocket server and then sending and receiving data on the connection.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] Promise-based interface for connecting to a WebSocket server; uses streams to send and receive data on the connection.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] The event sent by the WebSocket object when the connection closes.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] The event sent by the WebSocket object when a message is received from the server.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] An HTTP request header that contains a nonce from the client.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] This is used in the WebSocket opening handshake to verify that the client explicitly intends to open a WebSocket.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] It is added automatically by the browser.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] An HTTP response header used in the *WebSocket opening handshake* to indicate that the server is willing to upgrade to a WebSocket connection.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] The value in the directive is calculated from the value of `Sec-WebSocket-Key` in the corresponding request.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] An HTTP header that in requests indicates the version of the WebSocket protocol understood by the client.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] In responses, it is sent only if the requested protocol version is not supported by the server, and lists the versions that the server supports.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] An HTTP header that in requests indicates the sub-protocols supported by the client in preferred order.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] In responses, it indicates the sub-protocol selected by the server from the client's preferences.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] An HTTP header that in requests indicates the WebSocket extensions supported by the client in preferred order.
[src:websockets-browser/websockets-api] In responses, it indicates the extension selected by the server from the client's preferences.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] In this guide we'll walk through the implementation of a WebSocket-based ping application.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] In this application, the client sends a "ping" message to the server every second, and the server responds with a "pong" message.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The client listens for "pong" messages and logs them, keeping track of how many message exchanges there have been.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Although this is a pretty minimal application, it covers the fundamental points involved in writing a WebSocket client.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] You can find the complete example at https://github.com/mdn/dom-examples/tree/main/websockets.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The server side is written in Deno, so you'll have to install that first if you want to run the example locally.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] To communicate using the WebSocket protocol, you need to create a `WebSocket` object.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] As soon as you create this object, it will start trying to connect to the specified server.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The `WebSocket` constructor takes one mandatory argument — the URL of the WebSocket server to connect to.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] In this case, since we're running the server locally, we're using the localhost address.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The constructor takes another optional argument `protocols`, which allows a single server to implement multiple sub-protocols.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] We're not using this feature in our example.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The constructor will throw a `SecurityError` if the destination doesn't allow access.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] This may happen if you attempt to use an insecure connection (most user agents now require a secure link for all WebSocket connections unless they're on the same device or possibly on the same network).
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Creating a `WebSocket` instance starts the process of establishing a connection to the server.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Once the connection is established, the `open` event is fired, and after this point the socket is able to transmit data.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] If an error occurs while the connection is being established or at any time after it is established, the `error` event will be fired.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] On an error, the connection is closed and the `close` event will be fired.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] In our example we send text, but you can also send binary data as a `Blob`, `ArrayBuffer`, `TypedArray`, or `DataView`.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] A common approach is to use JSON to send serialized JavaScript objects as text.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The `send()` method is asynchronous: it does not wait for the data to be transmitted before returning to the caller.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] It just adds the data to its internal buffer and begins the process of transmission.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The `WebSocket.bufferedAmount` property represents the number of bytes that have not yet been transmitted.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Note that the WebSockets protocol uses UTF-8 to encode text, so `bufferedAmount` is calculated based on the UTF-8 encoding of any buffered text data.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] To receive messages from the server, we listen for the `message` event.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The server can also send binary data, which is exposed to clients as a `Blob` or an `ArrayBuffer`, based on the value of the `WebSocket.binaryType` property.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] When the connection is closed, because either the client or the server closed it or because an error occurred, the `close` event will be fired.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The back/forward cache, or bfcache, enables much faster back and forward navigation between pages that the user has recently visited.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] It does this by storing a complete snapshot of the page, including the JavaScript heap.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The browser pauses and then resumes JavaScript execution when a page is added to or restored from the bfcache.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] This means that, depending on what the page is doing, it's not always safe for the browser to use the bfcache for the page.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] If the browser determines that it is not safe, the page will not be added to the bfcache, and the user will not get the performance benefit that it can bring.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Different browsers use different criteria for adding a page to the bfcache, and having an open WebSocket connection may prevent the browser adding your page to the bfcache.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] This means it's good practice to close your connection when the user has finished with your page.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] The best event to use for this is the `pagehide` event.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Conversely, by listening for the `pageshow` event, you can seamlessly start the connection again when the page is restored from the bfcache.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] If you run our example, try navigating to a different page, then back to the example.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] In Chrome, you should see that the example starts the connection again, and keeps its original context: so, for example, it remembers the count of exchanged messages.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] See the web.dev article on the bfcache for more context on bfcache compatibility and the WebSockets API.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] On browsers that support it, you can use the `notRestoredReasons` property of the Performance API to get the reason a page was not added to the bfcache.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] WebSockets should not be used in a mixed content environment; that is, you shouldn't open a non-secure WebSocket connection from a page loaded using HTTPS or vice versa.
[src:websockets-browser/writing-websocket-client-applications] Most browsers now only allow secure WebSocket connections, and no longer support using them in insecure contexts.
